	<h1>Citation</h1>
	<p class="lead">What is a citation?</p>
</header>
<div class="row">
	<div class="span4">
		<p>A citation is a quotation from or reference to a book, paper, or author. We cite when we want to:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Make reference to a particular work by another author</li>
			<li>Give credit / Acknowledge contributions made by another author</li>
		</ul>
		<h3>Example</h3>
		<p>Let's look at the example on the right. The first thumbnail is a preview of <strong>In-line Citations</strong> made by an author. The citations appear in the body of a paper, and make reference to other papers. More details about the cited papers would appear in a paper's <strong>References</strong> section.</p>
		<p>There are various styles to display in-line citations. The most common styles are:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<div class="alert alert-info"><strong><i>< author names > [< number >]</i></strong></div>
				<p>
					To display authors' name, followed by an identifying number for the <strong>References</strong> section. This is the style used in our example.<p>Example:</p><i>...in the system described by <strong>John Doe [22]</strong>, it clearly states that...</i>
				</p>
			</li>

			<li>
				<div class="alert alert-info"><strong><i>(< author names >, < year of publication >)</i></strong></div>
				<p>To display authors' name, followed by the year of publication.<p>Example:</p><i>...in the system described by <strong>(J. Doe, 2011)</strong>, it clearly states that...</i>
			</p>
		</li>
	</ul>
