	<h2>What is a citing sentence?</h2>
	<p>
		You might already have a clue what is a citing sentence, we have already seen one in the examples. The <strong>citing sentence</strong> is/are the line(s) of words that contain the citation. For example in a part of a paper:
		<div class="alert alert-info">
			<p align="center">
				<i>...In this paper, we describe a system that will aid us in taking over the world. Previous works have all identified the key components needed for this task. In the system described by <strong>(J. Doe, 2011)</strong>, it clearly states that...</i>
			</p>
		</div>
	</p>
	<h2>What is cited information?</h2>
	<p>
		When an author cites another paper, his/her purpose must be to either refer to the cited paper as a whole, or refer to a particular piece of information in the cited paper. For example in the paper written by John Doe:
		<div class="alert alert-info">
			<p align="center">
				<i>...in order for a system to be successful in taking over the world, there are many components the system must have. <strong>Fundamentally, the system must have the ability to.........This enables us to...</strong></i>
			</p>
		</div>
		As you can see, the <strong>cited information</strong> is/are the line(s) of words that contain the most relevant information in relation to the citation made by the citing sentence.
